ian law was imposed upon a receptive and passive population. Challenges to authority, latent lawlessness, interaction between indigenous and settler societies, periods (pre- and post-1905) of jurisdictional confusion, and demands for individual, group, and provincial rights and recognitions are as much part of Alberta's legal history as the heroic and mythic images of an emergent and orderly Canadian west patrolled from the outset by red coated mounted police and peopled by peaceful and law-abiding subjects of the Crown. Papers focus on the development of criminal law in the Canadian west in the nineteenth century; the Natural Resources Transfer Agreement of 1930; the National Energy Program of the 1980s; Federal-Provincial relations; and the role and responsibilities of the offices of Justices of the Peace and of the Lieutenant-Governor; and the legacies of the Lougheed and Klein governments.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCivil rightszAlbertaxHistory. 0aConstitutional historyzAlberta. 0aLawzAlbertaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh  aCanadian History.1 aAnderson, Sandra M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAunger, Edmund A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBehiels, Michael D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Desmond, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavanaugh, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConnors, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConnors, Richard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFlanagan, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGibson, Dale, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca